en|There I journeyed, and found the oxen safe at home.The chief entertained me handsomely, and on the following morning I wentto pay my respects to him before leaving, and was somewhat surprised tofind a collection of some hundreds of men and women sitting round himanxiously watching the sky in which the thunder-clouds were banking upin a very ominous way.“You had better wait, white man,” said the chief, “and see therain-doctors fight the lightning.”I inquired what he meant, and learned that this man, Indaba-zimbi, hadfor some years occupied the position of wizard-in-chief to the tribe,although he was not a member of it, having been born in the country nowknown as Zululand.
en|But a son of the chief’s, a man of about thirty,had lately set up as a rival in supernatural powers.
